:::summary
*Beowulf* is the oldest surviving epic poem in the English language — a 3,182-line masterpiece of Old English poetry composed sometime between the 8th and 11th centuries. It tells the story of the Geatish hero Beowulf, who fights the monster Grendel, Grendel's mother, and finally a dragon, at the cost of his life. Rich in Christian and pagan themes, it is a profound meditation on heroism, loyalty, mortality, and the fate of civilizations.
:::

